Trance walked into Medical with a tray of various medicines and placed them down on the table. It had been almost a week since Rommie had come to there rescue, leading a troop of maintenance androids carrying force lances. The trip back to the Andromeda had been eerily silent after Rommie recounted what had happened since they had been taken off the ship.<br>
<br>
‘I can only assume that the missile had some kind of shielding or cloaking that hid it from my sensors. When it hit, it released a fast acting sleep inducer into the ship and a virus into my mainframe. The virus allowed them to come aboard and take you all off the ship. However, the new anti virus software that Harper installed managed to isolate and destroy it before the bounty hunters were able to place any overrides on my systems. As soon as the virus was destroyed I retook the ship using internal defences.’<br>
<br>
Rommie had described how she had tracked the aliens she’d identified as ‘Lendran’s’ back to their home planet and, when she had got close enough, had been able to pick up and trace Dylan’s sub-vocal microphone.<br>
<br>
Trance moved to sit next to one of the beds. She could feel tears welling up inside and despite her efforts; they started sliding down her cheeks. She leant her head down to the bed and sobbed silently.<br>
<br>
<br>
Harper noticed it was dark. He seemed to be spending a lot of time unconscious lately, but he couldn’t for the life of him remember why. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>‘Don’t even try to remember,’</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> His inner voice told him. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>‘Don’t you remember what happened the last time you opened your eyes? Just stay asleep and no one can hurt you again.’</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
Harper had never liked his inner voice, and despite what seemed like fantastic advice, he forced his eyes open and instantly wished he hadn’t. <br>
<br>
The light seemed to stab into the back of his skull. He could feel pain all down his spine, as if someone had ripped it out and inserted a red hot poker in its place. Every breath felt like his lunges were being rasped with sandpaper and his skull felt 3 sizes too small. He tried desperately to find some point on his body that didn’t hurt, but he failed miserably.<br>
<br>
As his eyes adjusted to the light, he started to make out details of the room he was in. Grey ceiling. As he tried to look around to take in more of his surroundings, pain blossomed again in his neck and spine. <br>
<br>
He slowly became aware of someone else next to him. Closing his eyes again, he concentrated on forcing back the waves of pain and nausea that were trying to overwhelm him and turned his head to the side.<br>
<br>
Joy welled up inside him and a tear ran down his cheek as he saw Trance sitting next to the bed, and he realised that he was lying in the sick bay on Andromeda. He noticed Trance was crying into her hands and hadn’t noticed him wake up. Using every ounce of his strength, he slowly moved his hand until he could place it on her arm. He licked his lips and tried to force himself to speak<br>
<br>
‘Trance….’<br>
<br>
She sat bolt upright, tears still falling down her cheeks but a smile spreading over her gorgeous face.<br>
<br>
‘Harper!’<br>
<br>
She leant over to hug him but remembered what had happened and settled on placing one hand on his forehead and the other on his arm. At her touch Harper instantly felt some of his pain ebb and he sighed quietly.<br>
<br>
‘We’ve all been so worried, you should have woken up days ago, but nothing I tried was working...’ she trailed off.<br>
<br>
Neither of them talked for a long time, they just sat and looked into each others eyes. Finally, it was Harper who broke the silence.<br>
<br>
‘Trance…what happened?’<br>
<br>
The golden pixie frowned slightly. ‘How much do you remember?’ she asked, concern showing in her voice.<br>
<br>
Harper closed his eyes and thought back. ‘I remember being taken out of my cell….then I saw the bench…then…’ his eyes widened. ‘I remember being shackled to the table. Then…nothing. What happened?’<br>
Trance closed her eyes and thanked the Devine that he couldn’t remember. His screams echoing around the cells were still giving her, and, although she didn’t know it, most of the crew, nightmares. As every second had passed they had thought Harper would crack and tell the bounty hunters what they wanted to know, but somehow he had found the strength to hold on. Gently, she rubbed his brow and ran her fingers through his hair. ‘Try to get some rest Harper, we can talk later.’<br>
Harper knew when she was avoiding a question; he had seen her do it enough times when he asked her about her home planet or her past.<br>
‘Trance, I want to know. What happened?’<br>
<br>
Trance looked unhappy and was silent for a long few moments. Finally, she answered, very quietly.<br>
‘They…Harper, they tortured you…’ <br>
<br>
Harper closed his eyes. He couldn’t remember. Neurology wasn’t something he claimed to know anything about, but the fact that his brain had stopped him remembering probably indicated that it had been very, very bad. ‘How long?’ he asked, his voice almost a whisper.<br>
<br>
Trance glanced down. She hadn’t meant to tell him that he’d been tortured; she didn’t want to remind him about it or awaken any memories. Quietly, she whispered ‘Almost three hours...Then Rommie rescued us’<br>
<br>
Harper closed his eyes again. ‘A new record,’ he murmured. He thanked all the Gods he believed in and a good few that he didn’t that he couldn’t remember any of it. The memories of his other encounters with torture equipment still gave him nightmares, and from what he could tell, those were just a walk in the park compared with his latest adventure. He felt himself slipping into sleep again so he let the darkness claim him…<br>
<br>
Over the next few days, Harper started his slow recovery. Trance hovered by his bed every time he woke up, sometimes with other members of the crew, more often on her own. <br>
<br>
One day, while Trance was sitting next to him giving him another set of injections, he looked over to her and marvelled at how beautiful she looked. He realised that he had been putting off talking to her about their conversation the night before they had been attacked.<br>
Plucking up his courage, Harper asked, ‘Trance…do you remember what you said to me the night before….before all this happened?’<br>
<br>
Trance slowly stopped what she was doing and looked down at the floor, nodding. ‘I’m sorry Harper, I shouldn’t have said anything. I didn’t realise you didn’t feel the same way. I…I hope we can still be friends.’<br>
<br>
The sheer pain in her eyes ripped through Harper like a nanowelder and made his own pain seem insignificant by comparison. She sat down by the bed with her head still down, not looking at him. He reached out and tipped her head up and looked at her again. All her inner defences and barriers were gone and for a second Harper could see the innocent sparkly purple babe that had been long buried under the tough, golden exterior. In an instant all his fears were gone. He knew that she loved him and that he felt the same way towards her. <br>
<br>
‘No, Trance, I’m the one who should apologise. I was scared that…that…’ he shook his head. ‘I’m not sure what I was scared of. I tried to push you away and I hurt you. Trance, I never want to hurt you like that again.’ Harper paused before continuing. ‘I remember thinking about what would happen if I tried to fight back against those bounty hunters. I saw them killing me and then taking you to be tortured instead. Trance, I could never let that happen to you.’<br>
<br>
As Trance listened, she realised what Harper had done. He had let himself be tortured for almost three hours to save her from having to go through the same thing. ‘Harper, I....’ she started, only to be interrupted. <br>
<br>
‘Trance, I need to say this, I need you to know…I love you Trance.’<br>
<br>
As soon as he said it, he felt a weight lifted from him that he hadn’t ever noticed was there. It felt RIGHT and it was easier to say than he could have ever hoped. He watched her eyes light up as she leant forward to hug him. Stopping short as she remembered the extent of his injuries, she brushed his cheek with her fingers. <br>
<br>
Trance hadn’t been able to work out why things hadn’t played out like in her vision. Suddenly, she realised that if she had said nothing, Harper would have attacked the guards simply to get away from being tortured, and he would have been killed. But because he knew she loved him and he had realised how he felt towards her, he had changed his own future. Her father’s words came back to mind as she leant over him again.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>‘Trance, even when everything seems to be lost, when every step forward seems a step closer to death and destruction, love can bring you through. You must cast aside all your fears and follow your heart.’</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Despite the pain that still flowed through Harpers body, he knew he would get better. He knew that Trance would be with him always.<br>
<br>
As their lips met, Harper noticed with satisfaction that his lips were the only part of him that didn’t hurt….<br>
<br>
Fin.<br>
